{"annotations": [{"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T-cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7884177565574646, "span": {"begin": 0, "end": 7}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "dendritic cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.84393310546875, "span": {"begin": 72, "end": 87}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3107"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Major Histocompatibility Complex", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.982399046421051, "span": {"begin": 91, "end": 123}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3133"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MHC", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.979315996170044, "span": {"begin": 125, "end": 128}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3107"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MHC molecules", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9897615909576416, "span": {"begin": 229, "end": 242}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3107"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "MHC molecule", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9800516366958618, "span": {"begin": 346, "end": 358}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3133"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MHC", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9844893217086792, "span": {"begin": 451, "end": 454}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:445347"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "T-cell receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9386112689971924, "span": {"begin": 534, "end": 550}}, {"id": ["CL:0000084"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T-cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8944255709648132, "span": {"begin": 671, "end": 677}}, {"id": ["CL:0000813"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "memory T-cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5804988741874695, "span": {"begin": 706, "end": 719}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "skin dendritic cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8121820092201233, "span": {"begin": 790, "end": 810}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "memory T-cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8663172721862793, "span": {"begin": 818, "end": 832}}, {"id": ["mesh:D017449"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "allergic contact dermatitis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999539256095886, "span": {"begin": 845, "end": 872}}], "text": "T-cells are typically affected by protein-hapten complexes presented by dendritic cells on Major Histocompatibility Complex (MHC) molecules. Molecular understanding of this process has improved in recent years (see[1]). Briefly, MHC molecules are membrane proteins which present the small peptide antigens placed in a &ldquo;groove&rdquo; of the MHC molecule during its intracellular synthesis and transport to the cell surface. In the context of the MHC molecular on the cell surface, the small peptide antigen is recognized via the T-cell receptors as self or non-self (e.g. foreign). If this peptide is a foreign peptide, such as part of a protein-hapten complex, the T-cell will be activated to form a memory T-cell, which subsequently proliferates. If reactivated upon presentation by skin dendritic cells, these memory T-cells will induce allergic contact dermatitis[2].", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:32:10 +0000 2026"}